name: Ann Martin
bio:
Hunter / Gatherer / Sharer. Papercraft book author and blogger at allthingspaper.net
Delaware, U.S.

social_posts.post_text: Leah Nikolaou (@leah_nikolaou_embroidery/) creates pretty, feminine wool embroidery designs that are accented with pressed flowers from her garden and turned into high quality giclée prints, ready for you to add your stitches. Leah is in the Artist Spotlight on the allthingspaper (.net) blog this week… get to know her via the link in my bio LinkTree.

CONGRATULATIONS to the the winners! @dani_lima27, @quillinggarden, and tdkidd (who entered via the blog post). 🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉Take a chance on winning Mayumi Fukuda's popular video course for Domestika! This giveaway is open WORLDWIDE.⁣
⁣
Mayumi (@mayumiorigami) is an origami jewelry artist who teaches her complete process via Paper Jewelry-Making with Origami Techniques, an online Domestika course. It has 97% positive reviews and over 2800 students since its July launch.⁣
⁣
A sampling of reviews:⁣
⁣
“I absolutely loved this course, Mayumi Fukuda is excellent at explaining which materials and techniques to use, as well as why and when to use them. There are also so many additional resources for materials and tutorials that are outside the scope of this course so you can continue to explore origami if you want to.” ⁣
⁣
“This course is incredibly fun and incredibly inspiring. The step-by-step instructions are very detailed, so you can easily create the most beautiful pieces of paper jewelry yourself.”⁣
⁣
To enter:⁣
⁣
1. Like this post⁣
⁣
2. Name your favorite origami model - perhaps a crane, boat, lotus or another of your choice
⁣
3. Be sure you are following @mayumiorigami and @allthingspaper⁣
⁣
4.⁣ Earn an extra entry: tag a friend in a separate comment who you think might also like to take the course⁣
⁣
THREE WINNERS will be selected at random on Sunday, December 4 from combined entries here on IG and the All Things Paper blog (link in bio). Yes, you may enter both places to double your chances.⁣ 😀
⁣⁣⁣
MORE ABOUT THE COURSE: Mayumi will teach you to create an exclusive solid, water-resistant origami jewelry set (necklace and earrings) using your own kimono-inspired, hand painted paper. No previous experience is required. Lifetime access. ⁣⁣Audio is in English and subtitles are offered in eight additional languages: English, German, Portuguese, Spanish, French, Dutch, Italian and Polish.⁣⁣ ⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Can’t wait to get started?! Sign up for the course via Mayumi’s direct link on her profile. ⁣
⁣
This giveaway is sponsored by Mayumi Fukuda via product barter.
⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣
⁣

At this hectic time of year, I invite you to take a moment to unwind via the serene paper art and words of Lubasha Sol (@pearlpapercouture). She is in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog this week - link in bio.

How nice to see that this holiday card tutorial by @lcipaper and posted on allthingspaper.net has been shared by @todayshow! It tops the list of 22 handmade card ideas. 😍 Check them out via the link in my bio.

If you haven't come across @mierpapier until now, you've been missing out! Miranda Mulder creates small, detailed paper mache monster and animal sculptures that are a total hoot. 😄

She's in the Artist Spotlight over at allthingspaper.net if you'd like to get to know her. Link in bio.

And so we’ve turned the page to 2023! @paper_to_jewellery arranged to have this handsome calendar sent to me from the UK @quillingguild. It features many examples of inspiring paper quilling created by Guild members.⁣
⁣
If you aren’t familiar with the organization, it is celebrating its 40th anniversary, is non-profit and run by volunteers. Membership is £10 GBP annually to read the magazines online and keep in contact with members around the world. Print versions are available if you prefer, as well as technique videos. Check it out!

Each year around this time I do a recap of paper items given and received during the holidays as it gives me a chance to highlight paper art and artists - which is exactly what I like to do! ⁣
⁣
This is just one example… a tiny house watercolor painting by @heathereddyarts. The gilded touches are 👌👏. ⁣
⁣
I’ll probably be posting a few more as Stories in the days ahead, but if you’re curious to see them all in one go, you know the drill… link in bio. 😀

I visited family in Florida during the holidays and even though the weather was about 40 degrees colder than I might have liked 🥶, it was a really nice trip made even better by a visit to Morikami Museum and Japanese Gardens (@morikamimuseum). ⁣
⁣
Why, you ask? Because I saw the exhibition, Washi Transformed: New Expressions in Japanese Paper. ⁣
⁣
Beautifully presented in three rooms are thirty works by nine paper artists from Japan, France, and the United States. Enjoy a sampling of photos and more info on the blog - link in bio.⁣
⁣
This nest-like piece composed of mizuhiki cord (pigmented washi) is part of a larger display titled 𝘑𝘢𝘱𝘢𝘯𝘦𝘴𝘦 𝘗𝘢𝘱𝘦𝘳 𝘚𝘵𝘳𝘪𝘯𝘨𝘴 𝘔𝘶𝘴𝘶𝘣𝘶 𝘙 by Ishii Kakuko of Japan.

Just a Worm is an engaging, new book for ages 4-8 by Marie Boyd (@artistscholar), published by @greenwillowbooks. Not only is the story delightful, but Marie has illustrated the cover and each page with colorful paper quilling. ⁣
⁣
Wonderful details are bound to capture the imagination of little ones and maybe even adults too (who just might learn a thing or two while reading it aloud). 😀⁣
⁣
Get to know Marie and the interesting way quilling found its way into her life via the allthingspaper.net blog post - link in bio.⁣
⁣
The book is available for pre-order on Amazon in the U.S. The release date is March 14, 2023.

This week's Artist Spotlight is shining on Caro Clarke of INKTERAKTIV (@inkteraktiv). I find her vibrant on-edge paper art endlessly appealing. ⁣
⁣
Perfectly constructed, Caro’s designs are minimalistic which, truth be told, are often a whole lot harder to execute than a piece with many parts. Why? Because one's eye naturally goes to any little out of place speck.
⁣
Get to know Caro and learn about her process and fave supplies via an interview on the blog - link in bio.

Cristiana Bellini of Les Petites (@_les__petites_) hand cuts decorative papers to create charming figures that are inspired by real life, as well as her imagination. ⁣
⁣
Many feature vintage fashions, but she also accepts custom requests, for example, modern day wedding couples dressed in their finery. Swipe to see an example. ⁣
⁣
Then take a minute to get to know Cristiana via the Artist Spotlight feature just posted over at allthingspaper.net - link in bio.

This week on allthingspaper.net I’ve rounded up eight international jewelry artists who are doing beautiful, creative work. Swipe to see several examples.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
1. necklaces by Silina Pandelidou (@silinarte) in Greece⁣⁣
2. necklace by Monica Peksa (@peksa.monica) in Austria⁣⁣
3. necklace by Lydia Hirte (@lydiahirte) in Germany⁣⁣
4. earrings by Jen Neame-Collins (@jen.neamecollins) in France⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Read about them and see lots more examples via the link in my profile. 😍

Always happy to collaborate with Mayumi Fukuda (@mayumiorigami) who makes perfect 𝘢𝘯𝘥 perfectly stylish folded paper jewelry. ⁣
⁣
She sent me these earrings in exchange for featuring her paper jewelry class that you’ll find on domestika.org. It’s a really popular course and no wonder as it’s high quality… just like Mayumi’s jewelry and packaging!

Lynda Wallis is this week's featured artist on the All Things Paper blog. After spending years as an illustrator/map maker, she is finally finding time to focus on her own art. This has led to the creation of vibrant abstract torn paper collages composed of many layers of found papers and natural bits from her garden.⁣
⁣
Get to know Lynda via the post link in my bio. Here on IG she's @braceletluv.

Every now and then I like to prowl around Etsy to find new-to-me papercraft kits. A dozen enticing ones caught my eye. ⁣
⁣
Here's an example: giant-size Zenflora flowers… they’re 18 inches in diameter! Such great decor for a party. ⁣
⁣
Designed by Stacey Stewart of LifesMomentsDesigns, the kit is one of several… another is printable. ⁣
⁣
Not into coloring? Then go au naturel as black and white looks striking on its own... swipe to see.⁣
⁣
You'll find the complete list of 12 on allthingspaper.net. A direct link is in my profile.⁣

Just wait until you see more of the floral book art created by Dr. Lisa Meek of BiblioBotany (@lemeekart). As a physician who specializes in cosmetic and restorative medicine, it's evident that her interest in artistry extends beyond that of the human form to the beauty and language of natural plants. ⁣
⁣
Lisa is in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog this week, which means an in-depth post about her altered books, process, and where you can see her art  in person. ⁣
⁣
The direct link is in my profile LinkTree. If you’re looking at this post in the future, visit allthingspaper.net and enter BiblioBotany in the search bar.

AI (artificial intelligence) art has been in the news quite often recently with good reason... it's both intriguing and perplexing to many of us. Will it replace human talent or enhance it? ⁣
⁣
On the blog this week three artists weigh in with their thoughts on AI-generated art... particularly paper art. There are lots of examples to see and questions to ask ourselves about the topic. ⁣
⁣
This collage by Polly Verity (@polyscene) was what started me thinking that the time was right for a post about AI after it received lots of attention when I shared it via my All Things Paper Facebook page. ⁣
⁣
Many people didn't grasp that it was AI-generated art despite the accompanying description. They weren’t familiar with the concept, plus it looks SO real, doesn’t it?
⁣
Several AI works by Marina Talamaska (@talamaskanka) are featured in the post too. Swipe to see a quilled design and a papercut bear for which she used AI. Often Marina utilizes Procreate or Photoshop to further enhance results after AI provides a starting point.⁣
⁣
Lastly, you'll see playful paper birds for which Chi Michalski (@chichiland) used AI.⁣
⁣
Click over to read what all three artists have to say about AI art via the link in my bio. If you're reading this post in the distant future, visit allthingspaper.net and search AI-Generated Paper Art to pull up the post.

Versatile quilling artist Tracy Balkin (@tracybalkin_paperart) of Johannesburg is featured in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog this week. Get to know her, including how she became fascinated by quilling, and see more examples of her commissioned pieces. Link in bio.

One of the aspects of blogging that I like most of all is that I get a chance to meet paper artists across the world. Sometimes they are making things I've never encountered before - and believe me, I've looked at lots of paper art in the twenty years since my fascination with paper arose. ⁣😀
⁣
Such was the case when I recently had the chance to ask Tian Shi (@tianshiwashibuto) of Brussels, Belgium about the unusual dreamlike washi figures he creates.⁣
⁣
Enjoy hearing about his work and what prompted him to begin making choreographed sculptures via this week's post on allthingspaper.net. Link in bio.⁣
⁣
If you're reading this post in the distant future and the direct link is no longer available, type Tian Shi in the blog's search box and you will find it.

It's been ages since I last sat down to design new quilled jewelry styles. Why? Don't know! But now I'm back with a step-by-step tutorial so you can make these three new styles of paper earrings. 
⁣
As you can see, there's a super-easy pattern, one that's a little busier, and then one that's more ornate than the others. ⁣Pick your pleasure. ⁣
⁣⁣
And surprise! I included a bonus fourth design in the how-to that just might be my favorite. 😍⁣
⁣⁣
The beauty of quilling is that it requires very few supplies... you probably have on hand everything that's needed to get started. If you try it and like it, you can order specialty papers like the metallic-edge strips that I used to make these examples. But even that kind of quilling paper is not expensive... it's just paper after all. ⁣
⁣⁣
You'll find the tutorial on my blog, allthingspaper.net. And all this week and next, just click the direct link in my bio LinkTree to get started on a creative new hobby.

If you missed my previous post about making quilled paper earrings, you’ll find a free step-by-step tutorial for making this style and three other designs over at allthingspaper.net. And yes, they are truly durable, don’t worry!

Have you seen the teeny tiny silhouette Minuances that KK Bicalho (@kk.bicalho) cuts by hand? Each one captures a moment of daily life, elevating it to something extra special. ⁣
⁣
KK is in the Artist Spotlight on the blog (allthingspaper.net) all this week. Enjoy reading what she has to say about her art. Link in bio.

A nod to Earth Week on the All Things Paper blog: Meet Roman artist Anna Maria Scocozza (@scocozzaannamaria) spins and weaves poetic garments and accessories using paper and plastic that would otherwise be discarded.⁣
⁣
Her work is currently on display at the Viviane Fontaine International Paper Triennial at Musée de Charmey in Switzerland.⁣
⁣
Anna Maria is in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog - link in bio - or if you are reading this in the distant future, visit allthingspaper.net and type Scocozza in the search bar to locate the post.⁣

True fact: this stunning paper lilac stem was made with quilling strips that are just 1mm wide! The narrow width brings new possibilities to quilled designs... coils that can be shaped to resemble paper sculpture, plus there’s no visible center hole. 

Learn all about 1mm strips and a number of other quilling supplies that are equally unique and useful in this week's blog post on All Things Paper. Link in bio or if you’re reading this in the distant future, enter quilling supplies in the search box.

The lilac was quilled by Lisa Haas (@thepaperquillingshop) who is the only seller of 1mm strips in the U.S. She also carries a fine-tip tool that’s ideal for working with them and a kit to get you started.

Do you know that Canson Mi-Teintes paper is now available as pre-cut quiling strips? Lisa Haas (@thepaperquillingshop) began cutting Canson strips from large sheets after hearing that quilling pros Yulia Brodskaya and Cecelia Louie use this brand of soft, but substantial paper. She quickly came to love it due to how beautiful it is when placed on-edge, plus it coils well and holds its shape. ⁣
⁣
Lisa realized that no supply sites were offering the strips so she uses her cutting machine to make all 46 Canson colors available in 1/8" (3mm) and 1/4" (6mm) widths via her Etsy shop, CustomQuillingByLisa. Right now she is only able to ship to U.S. and Canadian residents.⁣
⁣
(Swipe to see additional unique, but useful quilling supplies.)⁣
⁣
Another item that Lisa noticed was missing from quilling supply sites in the U.S. was 1mm strips. She imports these strips that give quilling an incredibly fine look along with a tool that rolls them into coils that appear sculptural. Another plus is that it leaves no center crimp.⁣
⁣
Jess Janiak (@tillyviktor) sells template card and envelope packs via her UK Etsy shop that are brilliant. Each card is printed with very pale lines that pave the way to perfect strip placement.⁣
⁣
Another handy tool she offers is a glue brush applicator that provides ease in landing a bit of glue exactly where needed.⁣
⁣
Check out both of these shops to see what other novel quilling items are available. Direct links are in my bio LinkTree.

⁣
Quilling Flowers, a beautiful new book by Sena Runa (@senaruna), will be released in the U.S. next Tuesday, May 9. ⁣🎉🎉🎉
⁣
To celebrate, GMC Publications will be sending the book to SIX lucky people (US and UK), three here on Instagram and three more who enter on the allthingspaper.net blog. ⁣
⁣
Yes, you may enter both places to double your chances! A direct link to the post is in my bio LinkTree.⁣
⁣
⁣⁣⁣The book is perfect for beginners, but the modern projects are also inspiring for quillers who have been paper rolling and shaping for years. ⁣
⁣
Within the 136 pages you’ll find step-by-step instructions and photos, a template for each of the twenty flower projects, as well as info about getting started, tools and materials, and techniques. ⁣
⁣
To enter do these things:⁣
⁣
1. Like this post.⁣
⁣
2. Post a comment.⁣
⁣
3. Earn extra entries by tagging friends separately who you think will also enjoy the book.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
4. Be sure you are following @allthingspaper and you might also want to follow @senaruna and @gmcpublications.⁣
⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣Winners will be notified on May 7. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
Good luck!⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣

You'll find the complete tutorial for this pretty honeysuckle blossom on the allthingspaper.net blog - link in bio LinkTree. It's one of twenty projects included in @senaruna's newest book, Quilling Flowers (released today in the US!) for @gmcpublications.

Meet collage artist iELA SNOW (@ielasnow_art) whose colorful, detailed work is composed of papers from around the world. Memories from past experiences provide inspiration. 

I’m happy to feature her in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog - link in bio.

Self-taught artist Nikki Besser (@niftynikkiart) creates extraordinary, large-scale quilled works that look (from a distance) as if they could be paintings. Each one has me wanting to know the story behind the characters. Enjoy an in-depth interview with Nikki on the All Things Paper (.net) blog. Link in my bio LinkTree.

While traveling recently, I came across a new-to-me type of sculpted, handcarved paper art in a hotel lobby. On the allthingspaper.net blog, meet the creator, Jennifer Falck Linssen, who uses an ancient Japanese papercarving technique called katagami to create modern wall art. The second image is a close up look at a piece called Wind in the Willows. 
⁣
Jennifer (@jenniferfalcklinssen) hasn't had much time to update her IG feed the past couple of years as her large-scale art is in demand for public spaces and private collections - a nice problem for an artist to have! I’m happy to say she sent over several recent pics that are included in the blog post. ⁣
⁣
You’ll find the direct link in my bio LinkTree.

Amy Bonsor's (@amybonsorart) stitched reliefs had me at hello... I love everything about them - the orderliness, texture, colors, even the perfect little needle holes that look like beads on a string. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Amy and her art are featured on the allthingspaper.net blog in the Artist Spotlight this week. Get to know her via the link in my bio Linktree. 😀👍

I've been a fan of Natalie Monday's colorful paper jewelry ever since @mondaymorningpress launched in 2019. Each pair of earrings is SO much fun, modern, lightweight, durable and sure to be noticed! ⁣
⁣
There are always fresh styles to see... each month and sometimes in-between, Natalie launches a brand new collection. ⁣
⁣
Tonight, Tuesday at 8 PM Eastern time, is the launch of Vacation Vibes. 🏖️ Sign up for text alerts via @mondaymorningpress so you'll have first dibs on the newest styles.

I put together a round up of the 2023 Etsy Design Awards Finalists that are items created with paper... this collage is just a small sampling. Even though voting has ended, there are quite a few beauties to enjoy, so have a look via the All Things Paper (.net) blog. Direct link is in my Story and bio LinkTree. ⁣
⁣
Clockwise:⁣
1. Kasa Pendant Lamp (Marina and Fumio Hirakawa of @24dstudio)⁣
2. Custom Papercut Map (Yang Cuevo of @paperhugger)⁣
3. Custom Paper Portrait (Mary Chau of @miniimoments)
4. Christmas Village Luminaries (Anne Louvau of @belgianpaperworks ) ⁣

In the Artist Spotlight this week are Allison Patrick (@craftimaven) and Vihra Rowe (@thepaperheartdesign). ⁣
⁣
First photo: Allie is a long-time maker of crepe paper flowers, but recently she's been upping her game via @LiaGriffith's Paper Flowers Membership. She's learned to add fine detail in construction and color, and is beginning to create her own floral designs. 
⁣
Second photo: Vihra Rowe (@thepaperheartdesign) is your go-to gal if you want to try your hand at crepe paper flower making, but would rather not attempt a whole course. She sells highly reviewed DIY tutorials and templates for a multitude of individual flowers and plants via her website and Etsy shop, The Paper Heart Design.⁣
⁣
You can read more about these artists on the allthingspaper.net blog. The direct link is in my bio Linktree, or if you're reading this in the distant future, just do a quick search on the blog for Stunning Crepe Paper Flowers and the post will pop right up. ⁣
⁣

CONGRATULATIONS TO THE WINNERS: @jessysuesunsweet and graphk4 / maki4355 on the blog. 🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉U.S. GIVEAWAY! Three lucky entrants will each receive a collection of specialty papers from @paperconnection.⁣
⁣
Located in Rhode Island, the company imports a wide selection of handmade fine art and decorative specialty papers from Japan, India, Nepal, Latin America, China, Korea and additional countries around the world. It is known for its excellent customer service. ⁣
⁣
To enter:⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣1. Heart this photo⁣⁣⁣
2. Post a comment⁣⁣⁣
3. Follow @paperconnection and @allthingspaper⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
The winner will receive 30 unique assorted cut pieces of handmade papers. ⁣
⁣
Approximate sizes: 5x7 and 7x10 inches and a few 4x5 inches.⁣
⁣
1st runner up will receive 15-20 pieces of same. ⁣
⁣
2nd runner up will receive 8-10 pieces of same.⁣
⁣
This giveaway is also underway on allthingspaper.net - direct link in bio LinkTree - and yes - you may enter both places to double your chances! 😀⁣
⁣
Winners will be selected from combined blog and Instagram entries by a random number generator on Sunday, July 16, notified, and announced here and on the blog.⁣
⁣
RECEIVE A DISCOUNT - All Things Paper followers will receive 10% off most Paper Connection items with use of coupon code: ATP2023 - July 11 through September 29, 2023.⁣
⁣⁣
This giveaway is sponsored by Paper Connection.

I've finally found a dupe for my all-time favorite fine-tip slotted quilling tool AND it's easy to get and is much less expensive!⁣
⁣
A set of JUYA fine-tip slotted quilling tools is sold in Etsy shop CustomQuillingByLisa and via Lisa’s website (@thepaperquillingshop), along with two types of unique quilling strips... imported 1mm strips, as well as Canson Mi-Teintes Ultra Premium paper strips that she cuts from large sheets. Her shop is the only U.S. supplier of these types of strips and the only place to buy a set of two JUYA fine-tip tools.⁣
⁣
On the All Things Paper blog I'm featuring a comparison of this new-to-me tool to my other favorite Japanese tool, as well as chatting about more quilled earring designs... send help... I can't stop making them!!⁣
⁣
A direct link to the post is in my bio LinkTree this week. In the future, search Fine-Tip Quilling Tool Comparison on allthingspaper.net and the post will pop right up.

In the Artist Spotlight this week, we hear from Mandy Duncan (@curlpaper) who tells about her work as a designer of paper fashion for magazine photoshoots and runway shows. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Also, enjoy a look at the paper costumes she made that awarded her the awesome prize of an around the world flight for two!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You'll find the blog post link in my bio LinkTree. If you're reading this in the future, visit allthingspaper.net and type paper couture in the search box.

Did you catch this week’s Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog? Meet Melbourne paper artist Mandy Duncan who went from making paper roses at a craft fair to designing paper couture for high profile magazine shoots and runway shows. Link in my bio LinkTree and Story.

These classic woven earrings from KAGOTOPIA are made of a new to me recycled paper product from Japan called Craftband. Have you heard of it? ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Find out more on the All Things Paper blog where this week's post is a round up of seven special paper jewelry artists who are making unique and pretty things.

Raphaela Pareto (@raphacchan) is a versatile artist and illustrator whose paper jewelry caught my eye. For example, this paper strip, pearl, and gold leaf ear cuff. ⁣
⁣
Find out more on the All Things Paper (.net) blog where this week's post is a round up of seven artists who are making unique and pretty jewelry with paper.

Christina Destrampe of Milwaukee Mandalas (@milwaukeemandalas) has fully embraced the process of using a Silhouette Portrait to create multilayer paper cuttings electronically. Between fulfilling commissioned pieces, stocking six Wisconsin shops, and leading monthly classes, in addition to being a sign language interpreter/teacher and mom to two little boys, she's one busy, but organized gal.⁣
⁣
I knew very little about cutting machines before featuring her on the All Things Paper blog, but after chatting with Christina and perusing her website, I feel like I have a much better grip on the process now and can see why it appeals to so many paper crafters. ⁣
⁣
Get to know Christina, her process, and see lots more paper cuttings via the link in my bio LinkTree. ⁣
⁣
If you're reading this in the distant future, just go to allthingspaper.net and type Milwaukee Mandalas in the search box and the post will pop up.

Anna Kruhelska (@foldiful) is in the Artist Spotlight on the All Things Paper blog. Formerly an architect, she now creates stunning contemporary wall reliefs. ⁣
⁣
This is a detail shot of one of her perfectly constructed plywood sculptures, BUT she also works with paper in equally outstanding ways. ⁣
⁣
Swipe to see an example and then visit the link in my bio LinkTree for more.

In the Artist Spotlight this week on the All Things Paper blog you'll meet quilling artist Jennifer Stacey (@jstacey_quillingfun). Since discovering quilling via Yulia Brodskaya's fine work a decade or so ago, Jennifer has been commissioned to create hundreds of personalized quilled pieces. Some are incredibly detailed as she works closely with clients to incorporate their wishes.⁣
⁣
 An early adopter of electronic cutting machines, Jennifer figured out how to utilize a Cricut in order to speed up the process by scoring the design. She also uses Cricut Design Space or the Procreate app to design the basic idea. ⁣
⁣
To read the full interview, the link is in my bio. If you're reading this in the future, visit allthingspaper.net and type Jennifer Stacey in the search bar. I know you'll enjoy hearing about her quilling journey and how she manages to get so much accomplished!

Dezhi Zhang, aka Mr. Anan, of Nan Paper Art in Shanghai, China heads up a team of remarkable paper artisans who use a variety of techniques to create breathtaking installations.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Their work has been featured in luxury brand advertisements, event spaces, store windows, at weddings, restaurants, and as home decor. Often the projects are large-scale... then again, they also do small-scale quilling. 😀 Swipe to see examples.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
@nanpaper_art is featured on the allthingspaper.net blog this week... link in bio LinkTree.

In the Artist Spotlight on All Things Paper (.net) this week, you'll meet Anastasiya Bertova in Dubai who crafts incredible floral arrangements using quite a few quilling techniques that are of her own invention. ⁣
⁣
Swipe to see a few examples of @anastasiya_bertova’s remarkable creations and get to know her via our interview on the blog. ⁣
⁣
The link is in my bio LinkTree or just search Bertova if you’re reading this post sometime in the future.

Perhaps you're like me and have been curious to know more about digital quilling and papercutting, as well as learn how to do them? 🤔 
⁣
On the All Things Paper blog this week, you’ll meet graphic artist Laurie Russell (@laurierusselldesign). She tells why she began creating digital art, explains why it is useful, and introduces her online courses that are available on Skillshare or her own Course + Community site. 
⁣
All Things Paper followers get a 20% discount on Laurie’s digital quilling or digital paper cutting courses via her new Course + Community site through the end of October. Use code ATPBLOG20. ⁣
⁣
Each course includes a Community area where students can share their art, ask questions, get feedback, and make connections. ⁣
⁣
You’ll find a direct link to the blog post in my bio LinkTree.

CONGRATULATIONS to the three winners! Pamela Haskin, Valdaree, and Pixiemom have been notified. 🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉 Get a jump on creating holiday cards and gifts with this stunning selection of metallic edge quilling strips from Quilled Creations!⁣
⁣
The U.S. company owned by quilling artist and how-to book author, Alli Bartkowski, and her husband Dave offers a wide selection of high-quality quilling papers, kits, tools, and accessories.⁣
⁣
The beauty of quilling is that it is a relaxing hobby that by its nature can't be done hurriedly, so now is a great time to begin creating quilled Christmas cards, framed art, and jewelry.
⁣
